Building the message base
*************************

   MailArchiver stores your messages and replies in a message base.
Each message base is made of four files. If the name of the base is
@{b}foo@{ub}, the names of those files will be:

  1. foo_msg (messages file)

  2. foo_msg.index (index of messages file)

  3. foo_reply (replies file)

  4. foo_reply.index (index of replies file)

   The index files are automatically created, if MailArchiver don't
find them when trying to open the messages and replies files. This
means that if your index files ever get corrupted, just delete them !

   To add your messages and replies to the message base, you just have
to call MailArchiver with the name of the message base as first
argument, and the name of the file storing the messages or the replies
as other arguments. So, the command line is as follow:

   MailArchiver <base> files... dirs...

   You can supply several file names, and even directory names:
MailArchiver will process all the given files, and all the files in the
given directories. Take care that the program will ignore
sub-directories.

   Each file may contain:

  1. a single message

  2. several messages, put one after the other

  3. a single reply

  4. several replies, put one after the other

   MailArchiver supports returned mail, that is messages which subject
is @{i}Returned mail: <reason>@{ui}. Other forms of messages enclosed in
messages or replies may not be supported.  The @{b}mail.received@{ub} and
@{b}mail.sent@{ub} files, generated by the Amiga version of @{i}Elm@{ui}, should be
processed without problem.

   In order to reduce the size of the replies base, MailArchiver is
able to detect and remove your signature. If you want to use this
feature, you just have to set the MAILARC_SIGNATURE variable to the
name of the file containing your signature, for example:

   setenv MAILARC_SIGNATURE UULIB:gounelle.signature

   Messages on which MailArchiver reported an error will not be added,
but before you add new messages and replies to a message base, it is
strongly recommended to backup your base. This way, you will be able to
restore it if something goes wrong.


@EndNode

@Node "Browsing" "MailArchiver.guide/Browsing"
@Next "Notes"
@Prev "Building"
@Toc "Main"

Browsing the message base
*************************

   To read the messages and replies stored in the message base, you
just have to enter a command like:

   MailArchiver <name of you base>

   A window will appear, showing the message list, sorted by date. Each
line correspond to a message, and shows it's date, sender address, and
subject. The number of messages is displayed in the titlebar of the
window. You can use the slider and the arrow gadgets to browse the list.

   To view the text of a message, you must have set the MAILARC_READER
variable to the name of your favorite text reader program. This can be
done with the @{i}setenv@{ui} command:

   setenv MAILARC_READER "SYS:Utilities/MultiView"

   Once you have set this variable, double-click on the line describing
the message: the text of the message will be extracted from the message
base, and the text reader program will be called to display it.  You
may use the <ESC> key to terminates the program.

   Other functions are available using the "Project" menu :


 @{" Show " Link "ShowItem"}          Select displayed list
 @{" Sort " Link "SortItem"}          Select sort order
 @{" Save " Link "SaveItem"}          Save current message to a file

   @{b}*@{ub} Redraw (Redraw all window)

   @{b}*@{ub} About (Display program information)

   @{b}*@{ub} Quit (Exit program)


@EndNode

